---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-korea', text: 'Leaving Korean Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pension-system', text: 'National Pension (NPS)', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-korea', text: 'Returning to Korea', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'South Korea D-8 Visa Insurance', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-south-korea-d8-visa' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'koreanSupport', header: 'Korean Support' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'koreaCoverage', header: 'Korea Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', koreanSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Strong', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$190/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', koreanSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Excellent', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$210/mo' },
  { provider: 'Samsung Fire & Marine', koreanSupport: 'Full (Korean)', usNetwork: 'Good', koreaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'DB Insurance', koreanSupport: 'Full (Korean)', usNetwork: 'Good', koreaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', koreanSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Good', koreaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$185/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Korean Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Korean expats. Find coverage with Korean support for the US, Canada, Australia, and other popular destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Korean Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Korea's excellent national health insurance doesn't travel abroad. Here's how to stay protected while preserving your options for returning home."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/korean-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Korean expats are concentrated in the US, Canada, Australia, and increasingly in Southeast Asia. Korean-language support and strong networks in these destinations matter. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Korean expats. Korean-language support, strong US networks (important for the large Korean-American community), reliable service.</li>
    <li><strong>Samsung Fire & Marine:</strong> Korean insurer with international products. Familiar brand, full Korean service, includes Korea coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>DB Insurance:</strong> Another major Korean insurer with competitive international offerings. Good value with Korean service.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent US and UK networks. Limited Korean support but top-tier coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices, though Korean support is limited.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Large Korean Community in the US"
    description="Los Angeles, New York, and Atlanta have significant Korean populations with Korean-speaking doctors and hospitals. Your insurer can help locate Korean-speaking providers."
    buttonText="Get Quote with Korean Support"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-korea">Leaving Korean Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Korea's National Health Insurance (국민건강보험) is mandatory for residents and provides excellent coverage. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Employee Insurance (직장가입자)</h3>
  <p>
    If you're leaving employment in Korea, your workplace health insurance ends when employment ends. Corporate expats on overseas assignments may continue under company coverage—check with your HR department.
  </p>

  <h3>Regional Insurance (지역가입자)</h3>
  <p>
    Self-employed or unemployed residents are covered under regional insurance. When you report your overseas relocation to your district office, this coverage ends.
  </p>

  <h3>Reporting Your Departure</h3>
  <p>
    Report your overseas relocation to the National Health Insurance Service (NHIS) before leaving. This officially ends your NHI coverage and premium obligations. Failure to report may result in accumulated premiums while abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Korean Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private insurance (실손보험) from Korean insurers typically provides limited international coverage—usually 30-90 days of emergency treatment. For long-term stays abroad, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="pension-system">National Pension (NPS)</h2>
  <p>
    Korea's National Pension Service (국민연금) has important implications for expats:
  </p>

  <h3>Voluntary Continuation</h3>
  <p>
    Korean citizens abroad can voluntarily continue NPS contributions. This protects your pension entitlement and is worth considering if you plan to return or want to maximize your pension.
  </p>

  <h3>Totalization Agreements</h3>
  <p>
    Korea has social security agreements with many countries including the US, Canada, Germany, and Australia. These prevent double contributions and coordinate pension rights.
  </p>

  <h3>Lump-Sum Refund</h3>
  <p>
    Foreigners leaving Korea may claim a lump-sum refund of their NPS contributions. Korean citizens typically maintain their pension rights rather than withdrawing.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Before You Leave</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Visit your local NHIS office and NPS branch before leaving Korea. They can explain your specific situation and help you decide on voluntary contributions and coverage termination.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Korean expats. They offer Korean-language support through their Asian operations, strong US networks (critical for the large Korean community in America), and comprehensive global coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited. Direct billing works at major hospitals worldwide. Korea coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats who want reliable global coverage with Korean-language support.
  </p>

  <h3>Samsung Fire & Marine Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Samsung is Korea's most recognized brand, and Samsung Fire & Marine offers international health insurance for Korean expats. Service is fully in Korean, the brand is familiar, and Korea coverage is included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    Networks are strong in Asia and adequate globally. Pricing is competitive with international insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats who prefer dealing with a familiar Korean brand and want seamless Korea coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>DB Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    DB Insurance (formerly Dongbu Insurance) offers competitive international health products for Korean expats. Full Korean-language service, Korea coverage included, and competitive pricing make this a solid alternative to Samsung.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats seeking good value from a Korean insurer.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent US networks. While Korean support is limited, English service is excellent. Plans are comprehensive including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Korean expats comfortable with English who want premium coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Korean and International Options"
    description="Korean insurers offer familiar service; international insurers often have stronger global networks. Compare both to find the best fit."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-korea">Returning to Korea</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Korean healthcare requires re-enrollment in NHI:
  </p>

  <h3>Re-registering Residence</h3>
  <p>
    Report your return at your local district office (주민센터) within 14 days. This triggers automatic NHI enrollment.
  </p>

  <h3>NHI Re-enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    You'll be automatically enrolled in NHI based on your employment status—either workplace insurance or regional insurance. Coverage begins immediately upon registration.
  </p>

  <h3>Premium Calculation</h3>
  <p>
    Premiums are calculated based on income, property, and other factors. If you had no Korean income while abroad, initial premiums may be lower but will adjust as your situation changes.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until you've confirmed your NHI enrollment. The process is usually quick, but having overlap coverage prevents gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep NHI while abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. NHI is for Korean residents only. When you report your overseas relocation, coverage ends. You need international health insurance abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What if I don't report my departure?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">You may be charged premiums while abroad and face penalties. Always formally report your overseas relocation to NHIS before leaving.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I continue NPS contributions?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">If you plan to return to Korea or want to maximize your pension, voluntary contributions are worth considering. Check totalization agreements for your destination.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Korean doctors in the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, especially in LA, NYC, and Atlanta. Koreatown in LA has extensive Korean-language healthcare options. Your insurer can help locate Korean-speaking doctors.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Samsung or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Samsung offers Korean familiarity and includes Korea coverage. Cigna has stronger global networks and Korean support. Compare based on your destination.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Korea visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Korean insurers include Korea coverage. International insurers offer it as an add-on. Without coverage, you pay full prices (no NHI subsidy).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Korean expats should prioritize comprehensive international coverage to replace Korea's excellent NHI system. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage with Korean-language support. <strong>Samsung Fire & Marine</strong> and <strong>DB Insurance</strong> are ideal for those who prefer Korean insurers.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those comfortable with English service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, report your departure to NHIS and consider voluntary NPS contributions if you plan to return. Ensure continuous coverage with no gap between Korean and international insurance.
  </p>

</PageShell>
